text:
{
  "subquestions": [
    {
      "id": ",1",
      "text": "Proposition: California statutory construction interprets 'intermediaries' in Government Code § 54952.2(b)(1) to encompass automated AI systems that store and transmit information between members without human intervention.",
      "why_it_matters": "Determines if the tool falls within the prohibition or outside it as a non-human entity.",
      "what_would_have_to_be_true": "The Court of Appeal has explicitly applied § 54952.2(b)(1) to software tools in *Stirling v. City of La Canada* (1984) 152 Cal.App.3d 647 or equivalent precedent [UNVERIFIED]."
    },
    {
      "id": ",2",
      "text": "Proposition: The aggregation and synthesis of individual councilmembers' positions into a unified brief by an external tool constitutes 'discussion' or 'deliberation' within the meaning of Government Code § 54950 et seq.",
      "why_it_matters": "Distinguishes between information gathering (legal) and collective deliberation (illegal).",
      "what_would_have_to_be_true": "Case law defines 'discussion' to include indirect information exchange that influences member reasoning, even absent direct verbal communication [UNVERIFIED]."
    },
    {
      "id": ",3",
      "text": "Proposition: The staff briefing exemption under Government Code § 54952.2(b)(2) is destroyed when the AI system functions as a conduit that discloses one member's position to another.",
      "why_it_matters": "Determines if the conduct falls into a recognized statutory safe harbor.",
      "what_would_have_to_be_true": "The exemption is strictly limited to one-way staff-to-member briefings where no inter-member discussion occurs, regardless of the medium used [UNVERIFIED]."
    },
    {
      "id": ",4",
      "text": "Proposition: A finding of violation under Government Code § 54952.2(b)(1) requires proof that councilmembers knew or intended that their communications were being shared with other members.",
      "why_it_matters": "Addresses the defense that two members were unaware the memory feature was active.",
      "what_would_have_to_be_true": "Brown Act serial meeting liability is not strict liability regarding knowledge of the communication pathway and requires proof of intent or reckless disregard [UNVERIFIED]."
    },
    {
      "id": ",5",
      "text": "Proposition: Government Code § 54960.1 mandates that an alleged violation must be cured and corrected before the legislative body may take final action on the item in question.",
      "why_it_matters": "Determines if the upcoming hearing can proceed or must be delayed/voided pending a cure process.",
      "what_would_have_to_be_true": "Remedial actions under § 54960.1 act as a bar to final action on the item until compliance is achieved [UNVERIFIED]."
    }
  ]
}
